<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-864-602  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 864 602.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Nov 6 1989 v6 n44 p4(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Word for Windows whets appetite for PM version. (Microsoft Corp.'sWord for Windows word processing software) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Picarille, Lisa.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (product introduction).andO;Ticker:    MSFT.andO;Product:   Microsoft Word for Windows (Word processing software) (productintroduction)OS/2 Presentation Manager (Graphical user interface) (computerprograms).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionSoftware PublishersPlanningOS-2Word processing softwareOS-2 (Computer operating system).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Lisa PicarilleandM;BOSTON -- Microsoft Corp. unmasked its long-awaited Windows-based wordprocessor here last week, heightening anticipation of news on a forthcomingWord version that runs under OS/2 Presentation Manager (PM).andM;That news shouldn't be too long in coming: Microsoft CEO Bill Gates said thefirm will reveal details of the Word for PM product at Comdex/Fall next week.andO;&quot;We'll make clear what our plan is to put [Word] on Presentation Manager,&quot; hesaid.andP;  &quot;We'll explain how we're doing that and when we're doing that, andwe'll give more details.&quot;andM;In demonstrating Word for Windows, Gates noted that it is a superset of whatis currently available to Word users on the Macintosh -- a trend that sourcessaid should continue into the next release.andP;  Word for PM will be a directport of the Windows product, said the sources, who were on the developmenteffort.andM;Word for PM is expected to take advantage of the PM interface to provideusers with a what-you-see-is-what-you-get interface and flexible textformatting.andP;  The program will also support dynamic data exchange.andM;The Redmond, Wash., firm used last week's announcement to highlight similarabilities in Word for Windows, showing the program importing data from theMicrosoft Excel spreadsheet, and enabling users to send E-mail and faxes fromwithin the application.andM;The PM version of Word, which is expected to carry the same $495 price tag asWord for Windows, will be released a few months after Word for Windows'January ship date, sources said.andO;</TEXT></DOC>